        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>237 S. Desplaines St.<lb/>
            Chicago&#44; April 27. 1877.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
            Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>In reply to your esteemed letter of the 23. inst. I have<lb/> to say that I tried to learn something in regard to Mr<lb/> S. Magyar&#44; and was informed of the following facts.  Said Mr<lb/> Magyar kept for a considerable time a hardware store on South<lb/> Halsted <sic>st.</sic> No 717 in this city.  His business was in the first<lb/> time flourishing&#44; but of late he had no success&#59; his<lb/> customers <sic>would&#39;nt</sic> transact anymore any business with<lb/> him&#44; his reputation being such that he became much<lb/> disliked with his neighbors.  In consequence thereof he sold<lb/> out&#44; and a few days ago he left Chicago to start a business<lb/> in Wisconsin.  One of my informers told me that he had<lb/> gone to Madison&#44; Wis.&#44; with the intention to commence<lb/> another business there&#44; if the prospects there would appear<lb/> good to him.<lb/></p>
            <p>About 2 years ago he married here a Miss Raffalsky&#44;<lb/> but children with this wife he has not.  Upon further<lb/> enquiry I was told that he was divorced from his first<lb/> wife by a decree of one of the Chicago Courts&#59; Mr. Philip<lb/> Stein&#44; a lawyer here&#8212;so I was informed&#8212;took steps<lb/> to have the wife in Europe summoned to come here&#44; but<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>as she declined to come&#44; a decree of divorce was<lb/> granted by the court.<lb/></p>
            <p>This is about all what I learnt of Mr Magyar<lb/> by enquiring about him among his former neighbors.<lb/></p>
            <p>Concerning &#40;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#41; &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; I was very much<lb/> pleased to read your note in the Jewish Record.  I saw<lb/> forthwith that the printer had done a bungling work in<lb/> setting your manuscript into type.<lb/></p>
            <p>Your translation of Luzzatto&#39;s Introduzione &#91;&#63;&#93; I<lb/> have read with great interest.  It is a pity that such<lb/> writings&#44; which appear piecemeal in Weeklies&#44; must so<lb/> soon fall into oblivion.  <hi rend="underline">Such</hi> labors deserve a better<lb/> fate.  They ought to appear in book form.<lb/></p>
            <p>I shall see some friends within the next days&#44;<lb/> and probably I can find one or the other amongst<lb/> them who will buy Luzzatto&#39;s commentary to the later<lb/> prophets.<lb/></p>
            <p>With best regards I remain<lb/>
            yours very truly<lb/>
            B. Felsenthal<lb/></p>
        </body>
